## 🎯 Overview
Introduces a revolutionary community-driven insurance system that creates a financial safety net for Justicebit escrow transactions, turning risk into opportunity through collective protection.

## ✨ New Features
- **Community Insurance Pool**: Shared fund protecting against escrow failures
- **Premium-Based Coverage**: Users pay 2% premium for up to 80% coverage
- **Judge-Validated Claims**: Rigorous 3-judge validation process for claim approval
- **Automatic Claim Processing**: Smart contract automatically processes approved claims
- **Proportional Rewards**: Contributors earn from premiums and share in pool growth
- **Risk Mitigation**: Comprehensive protection against fraud and unresolvable disputes

## 🔧 Technical Implementation
- 280+ lines of new Clarity code
- 4 new data maps for comprehensive insurance state management
- 6 public functions + 9 read-only functions for full insurance lifecycle
- Economic incentives aligned with platform security
- Zero breaking changes to existing escrow functionality

## 💡 Economic Model
- **2% Premium Rate**: Affordable protection for all escrow sizes
- **80% Max Coverage**: Prevents moral hazard while providing substantial protection
- **Community-Driven**: Contributors collectively own and benefit from the insurance pool
- **Judge Validation**: Leverages existing judicial system for claim validation
- **Self-Sustaining**: Premiums fund both payouts and contributor rewards

## 🎪 Use Cases
- **High-Value Transactions**: Protection for expensive purchases and services
- **Unknown Counterparties**: Added security when dealing with new sellers/buyers
- **Cross-Border Trade**: Extra confidence for international transactions
- **Business Operations**: Insurance for recurring commercial escrows

## ✅ Verification
- Contract compiles successfully with `clarinet check`
- All insurance functions integrate seamlessly with existing escrow system
- Comprehensive economic safeguards prevent abuse and ensure sustainability
- Ready for mainnet deployment and community adoption

release.body:
## 🚀 What's New in v1.0.1

### ✨ Enhanced Code Coverage Analysis
- 📊 **Per-class coverage analysis** with visual status indicators (🟢🟡🟠🔴)
- ⚠️ **Identify classes needing improvement** with specific targets and line numbers
- 🔍 **Display uncovered line numbers** for precise development guidance
- 🎛️ **Configurable coverage thresholds** (org-wide and per-class)

### 🔧 New Features
- `coverage_threshold` input parameter (default: 75%)
- `low-coverage-classes` output - count of classes below threshold
- `coverage-analysis` output - whether detailed analysis is available
- `worst-coverage-class` output - class with lowest coverage

### 📈 Enhanced Reports
```
## 📊 Code Coverage by Class
| Class Name | Total Lines | Covered | Uncovered | Coverage % | Status |
|------------|-------------|---------|-----------|------------|--------|
| AccountService | 150 | 140 | 10 | 93% | 🟢 Excellent |
| ContactService | 100 | 80 | 20 | 80% | 🟡 Good |
| LeadService | 75 | 34 | 41 | 45% | 🔴 Critical |
```

### 💡 Usage Example
```yaml
- name: Parse Test Results with Coverage Analysis
  uses: Infinite-Source-ark/apex-test-reporter@v1.0.1
  with:
    json_path: testout.json
    coverage_threshold: "80"  # Individual class threshold

- name: Check Coverage Issues
  if: steps.apex.outputs.low-coverage-classes > 0
  run: |
    echo "Found \ classes below threshold"
    echo "Worst coverage: \"
```

### 🔄 Backward Compatibility
- All existing outputs and functionality preserved
- Legacy field names still supported
- Graceful fallback when coverage data unavailable

**Full Changelog**: https://github.com/Infinite-Source-ark/apex-test-reporter/compare/v1.0.0...v1.0.1

This meta issue tracks scenarios where chat requests are blocked due to rate limiting.

👉 To get help with **premium request quota issues**, please comment in https://github.com/microsoft/vscode/issues/252230 .

In case you experience repeated rate-limiting in GitHub Copilot, please reach out to GitHub Support: https://support.github.com/

Error message:
> Sorry, your request was rate-limited. Please wait x minutes before trying again.

Most users see rate limiting for preview models, like OpenAI’s `o1-preview` and `o1-mini`, which are rate-limited due to limited preview capacity. Another cause is higher request/token usage for agent mode, which is still in _preview_ partially of this capacity

Service-level request rate limits ensure high service quality for all Copilot subscribers and should not affect typical or even deeply engaged Copilot usage. We are aware of some use cases that are affected by it. GitHub is iterating on Copilot’s rate-limiting heuristics to ensure it doesn’t block legitimate use cases.
